#Text=Wikinews interviews :
#Text=Tony Benn on U.K. politics
#Text=Sunday , August 12 , 2007
#Text=Tony BennCredit :
#Text=Josh Benn
#Text=Tony Benn , at 82 is a still an active political figure , attending rallies and giving speeches .
#Text=During the 1970s he served under James Callaghan as Energy Secretary , having earlier held the position of Secretary of State for Industry under Harold Wilson .
#Text=After a number of attempts to contact Mr Benn via email , he forwarded a telephone number for the purpose of doing an interview .
#Text=Following a brief discussion to explain who or what Wikinews is , and its relation with Wikipedia , Wikinews reporter Brian McNeil started putting the questions .
#Text=Mr Benn speaks at length on a variety of topics , this is the first article from this extended interview covering his views on New Labour and U.K. politics .

#Text=Contrasting the situation between Tony Benn 's time in government and the Tony Blair years Wikinews asked " In the last 12 years the Labour party had one leadership election which was ... ceremonial .

#Text=He said , New Labour is a new political party and when Mrs. Thatcher was asked her greatest achievement , she said  New Labour " .

column1: #Text=Therefore , the Labour victories in 97 [ ... ]
#Text=Blair victories have not really been Labour victories , they 've been victories for a party that based so much of its polices on the Thatcher inheritance .
#Text=And that 's why I 'm not a member of New Labour .
#Text=...
#Text=when Mrs. Thatcher was asked her greatest achievement , she said " New Labour " .
#Text=Wikinews asked about Tony Benn 's opinion of Gordon Brown , the United Kingdom 's new Prime Minister .
#Text=Gordon Brown 's roots are in the Labour movement , which Blair 's were not .

#Text=He understands the history of Labour movement , he is very much committed to market forces and globalisation but he 's a son of the manse and he 's entitled to a honeymoon and I think his early start has been very interesting .
#Text=He 's distanced himself discreetly from President Bush .

#Text=When he went to see Bush , Bush praised him and he praised the United States of America , which is an important thing and he choose to make his big speech at the United Nations about Darfur and now the paper today , I do n't know if that is true , suggest that British troops will be withdrawn from Iraq soon , I hope that is true .
#Text=He 's also made one or two very interesting constitutional proposals which would give greater power to parliament rather than be a presidential system and [ ... ]
#Text=also he 's made a request today for the return of all the British residents who 've been detained in Guantanamo Bay .

#Text=So my instinct is to give him a good start and the main thing is - Blair has gone - and I must admit , that is such a development , such an important development that my inclination is to try and give Gordon Brown an opportunity .
#Text=Wikinews asked if Tony Benn believed the U.K. should withdraw from Iraq .
#Text=Oh yes .
#Text=Well according to the papers today , it looks as if Brown may be planning to do that on the basis of the military advice he has received from the British general .
#Text=But that 's , I hope that 's true , but it is n't confirmed .

#Text=Well I think the contribution that Blair made to Bush was to pretend , help him to pretend that this was an international force , a coalition of the willing , where as if Britain refused to go in it would have been seen as a Vietnam and I think to that extent , Blair gave Bush what he wanted .
#Text=Bush did n't get , want ... or need British troops , but he wanted British political support and he got it .
#Text=And I think that political support is ending .
